1
00:00:00,385 --> 00:00:07,011
OK. OK. Three score years and 10.

2
00:00:07,953 --> 00:00:24,030
How did it come about that I should spend 12 hours of my 70th birthday sitting in silence or taking baby footsteps around a house in Portugal and then come back here to Satipanya to celebrate my official birthday with all of you?

3
00:00:24,992 --> 00:00:29,176
I think it traces back to summer holidays in my granny's house in Cork.

4
00:00:29,579 --> 00:00:31,702
and habit of the family rosary.

5
00:00:32,241 --> 00:00:36,607
Everyone gathered in the evening, knelt down and said the prayer together.

6
00:00:38,130 --> 00:00:46,439
Ireland in the 1950s was very much a Catholic country and Sunday mass and confession and so on were a big part of life.

7
00:00:47,502 --> 00:00:56,874
I don't think many families still kept up the practice of the daily rosary, but I'm very grateful that it was still alive in my granny's house while I was a child.

8
00:00:57,814 --> 00:00:59,417
The rosary is a prayer

9
00:00:59,633 --> 00:01:01,395
that takes about 15 minutes.

10
00:01:01,875 --> 00:01:10,665
There are five mysteries to contemplate, each one a different scene from the life of Christ or from his death and resurrection and beyond.

11
00:01:11,646 --> 00:01:18,933
Somehow it clicked with me to hold an image in the imagination of saying a very simple, repetitive prayer.

12
00:01:19,495 --> 00:01:25,682
It gave me a way of taking to heart what was taught as truly important and fundamental in life.

13
00:01:26,763 --> 00:01:28,424
It was a form of meditation

14
00:01:28,810 --> 00:01:34,115
bringing my mind to a quiet place where I could sense some connection with deeper truth.

15
00:01:35,376 --> 00:01:39,981
After the holidays, my mum, dad and brother, Conor and I, went back to Dublin.

16
00:01:40,783 --> 00:01:42,984
We didn't say the family rosary at home.

17
00:01:43,385 --> 00:01:48,311
It obviously didn't mean much to my mum or dad, and definitely not to my brother, Conor.

18
00:01:48,772 --> 00:01:55,539
He was a carefree and wild child, always getting into some sort of trouble, where I was dreamy.

19
00:01:55,959 --> 00:01:58,141
At least, that's how my granny described me.

20
00:01:58,409 --> 00:01:59,691
and I think she was right.

21
00:02:01,173 --> 00:02:11,426
So maybe because I liked dreamy images from the life of Christ, I continued the rosary on my own, though snuggled up in bed rather than on my knees on the cold floor.

22
00:02:12,229 --> 00:02:17,917
Climbing into bed, I'd be grumbling that I'd much prefer to daydream than say the rosary.

23
00:02:18,518 --> 00:02:23,163
But I'd make a bargain with myself to say just one mystery and then daydream.

24
00:02:23,645 --> 00:02:28,010
But when I got to the end of that first mystery, I decided to do a second

25
00:02:28,243 --> 00:02:32,149
and then daydream, and so on, till I got through all five.

26
00:02:32,609 --> 00:02:38,417
By that time, sleep beckoned, and I no longer had the energy to bother daydreaming.

27
00:02:38,437 --> 00:02:53,034
In retrospect, I'm very grateful for the family rosary practice, both because it put some limit on my habit of daydreaming, and because it was my first taste of meditation, a quieting of the mind as it opens in awe.

28
00:02:53,895 --> 00:02:55,617
I lost the habit as I grew older,

29
00:02:56,272 --> 00:03:05,481
Though I have no memory of deciding to stop, it may have been after what you might call my first spiritual insight, which came when I was eight.

30
00:03:06,242 --> 00:03:13,670
I was praying one evening when I suddenly knew that there was a presence beside and around me that was separate to me.

31
00:03:14,352 --> 00:03:16,813
It seemed to drop like a thud into my mind.

32
00:03:17,335 --> 00:03:24,542
One moment I was the only one in the room, then suddenly there was also this mysterious presence, which I took to be God.

33
00:03:25,568 --> 00:03:30,335
While I didn't feel God's presence was threatening, I didn't feel it as loving either.

34
00:03:30,855 --> 00:03:32,698
It was just there, other.

35
00:03:33,439 --> 00:03:45,617
The main way it affected me was to show me that I'd been making this big mistake, that all my thoughts of God and my prayers had all been make-believe, that I'd never known God till now.

36
00:03:46,258 --> 00:03:51,967
Maybe I got myself mixed up with the idea of false gods from the first of the Ten Commandments.

37
00:03:52,427 --> 00:03:53,449
Thou shalt not...

38
00:03:55,301 --> 00:04:01,546
Maybe I got myself mixed up with the idea of false gods from the first of the Ten Commandments.

39
00:04:01,567 --> 00:04:07,671
Thou shalt love the Lord thy God and thou shalt not put false gods before me.

40
00:04:08,872 --> 00:04:13,296
To my mind, I had committed a dreadful sin, made up a false image of God.

41
00:04:13,736 --> 00:04:19,322
The guilt multiplied up with the judgment that I'd never said any proper prayers in my life.

42
00:04:19,963 --> 00:04:22,305
Hundreds and hundreds of sins.

43
00:04:23,064 --> 00:04:25,107
And because I'd never confessed these,

44
00:04:25,305 --> 00:04:28,930
I'd made bad confessions, each one a mortal sin.

45
00:04:29,632 --> 00:04:35,800
And then I'd compounded that problem by going to communion with the mortal sin of a bad confession on my soul.

46
00:04:36,322 --> 00:04:40,348
And so I'd made bad communions, more mortal sins.

47
00:04:41,048 --> 00:04:49,800
Within a few minutes, I'd clocked up several hundred mortal sins, because in those days you went to confession and communion every week.

48
00:04:49,822 --> 00:04:55,009
The reason I know I was eight when this happened is because I had to multiply

49
00:04:55,208 --> 00:05:04,942
my two mortal sins per week for my bad confession and bad communion, by 52 for every year since my first communion, which was when I was five.

50
00:05:05,904 --> 00:05:12,314
Then I had to add in extra bad confessions and bad communions for all the feast days and Christmas days.

51
00:05:12,956 --> 00:05:21,790
And I found even more as I scoured through my little green catechism to be sure I'd got them all multiplied up correctly before my next confession.

52
00:05:23,254 --> 00:05:26,218
I imagine I stopped saying the rosary after that.

53
00:05:26,699 --> 00:05:30,002
There couldn't have been any joy or peace in it.

54
00:05:30,802 --> 00:05:46,221
Although the guilt probably undermined me subconsciously, the episode didn't mark my life at the surface level, which was a good thing.

55
00:05:47,040 --> 00:05:52,047
Beyond making sure I got to confession as soon as possible to get all my sins forgiven,

56
00:05:52,971 --> 00:05:59,839
I don't remember thinking about it much and I doubt anyone in the family or among my friends knew anything had happened.

57
00:06:00,521 --> 00:06:04,324
So that was the first phase of my religious life.

58
00:06:04,345 --> 00:06:11,314
Meditation, devotion, mystery, a thought of insight and then a plunge into guilt.

59
00:06:12,735 --> 00:06:14,838
In many ways, I had a happy childhood.

60
00:06:15,338 --> 00:06:19,523
My brother Connor was just a year older and we were very close.

61
00:06:19,744 --> 00:06:22,607
There were dozens of children our age living nearby.

62
00:06:23,009 --> 00:06:24,831
So always someone to play with.

63
00:06:25,612 --> 00:06:30,918
My dad worked as a weather forecast at the airport and we didn't have financial problems.

64
00:06:31,639 --> 00:06:39,767
However, there was always a background anxiety hanging over us because my mother had bipolar depression.

65
00:06:39,788 --> 00:06:46,656
It was first diagnosed as postnatal depression after Connor was born and then again after my birth.

66
00:06:47,617 --> 00:06:50,721
In those days, there was no psychotherapy available.

67
00:06:51,021 --> 00:06:54,185
or even much kindness in psychiatric practice.

68
00:06:55,826 --> 00:06:58,990
Just electric shock treatment and heavy sedation.

69
00:06:59,711 --> 00:07:01,954
And so she never really recovered.

70
00:07:02,555 --> 00:07:05,898
For much of our childhood, she was in bed and very depressed.

71
00:07:06,399 --> 00:07:19,492
And every six months or so, she would have an acute flare-up and get into rows with family or neighbours until eventually she had to be admitted to hospital again for more ECT and sedation.

72
00:07:20,300 --> 00:07:28,127
While she was in hospital, myself and my brother would stay with cousins, sometimes both at the one house, sometimes split up.

73
00:07:29,267 --> 00:07:31,629
At the time, I didn't see this as a problem.

74
00:07:32,170 --> 00:07:34,612
I liked my cousins and enjoyed staying with them.

75
00:07:35,153 --> 00:07:47,423
But I know now that my mother's illness took a toll at a deeper level and underlay my later midlife crisis and the fear that suddenly emerged during a retreat in 1999.

76
00:07:48,605 --> 00:07:49,985
Another major sorrow

77
00:07:50,302 --> 00:07:54,189
was that Conor's wildness caught up with him just after he turned 18.

78
00:07:55,370 --> 00:07:58,795
He went out to a dance one Saturday night and never came home.

79
00:07:59,697 --> 00:08:01,620
He was killed in a road accident.

80
00:08:02,641 --> 00:08:06,646
That was a devastating blow for all the family, as you can imagine.

81
00:08:09,651 --> 00:08:11,153
But life went on.

82
00:08:12,134 --> 00:08:17,543
Although I had lost the habit of the rosary, I never lost the sense of mystery that it kindled.

83
00:08:18,180 --> 00:08:33,964
there was a strong wish to understand the deeper truths of life, which was why I opted to study physics after school, on the assumption that understanding the basic law of physics meant I would understand life itself and be happy.

84
00:08:35,225 --> 00:08:40,734
But even before I finished college, I realised I was onto the wrong track.

85
00:08:40,754 --> 00:08:45,740
Nothing I was learning was helping me understand life better or be any happier.

86
00:08:46,732 --> 00:08:50,317
Though that was disappointing, there were lots of compensations.

87
00:08:50,738 --> 00:09:12,527
The physics class was small, only 12 of us, and we made good friends, hiking over mountains at the weekends, renting cottages in the country during holidays, playing tennis into the long summer evenings, frantic study before the exams, and of course, many pints of creamy gins to help us to put the word right.

88
00:09:13,427 --> 00:09:16,351
When I started college, a pint cost 18 pence.

89
00:09:16,669 --> 00:09:20,894
By the time I finished, it had gone up to a staggering 23 pounds.

90
00:09:22,697 --> 00:09:28,745
So college was a wonderful experience and our physics class still gets together frequently.

91
00:09:29,144 --> 00:09:37,515
In fact, we're having a collective 70th birthday party next month as we've all reached this milestone during the year.

92
00:09:38,836 --> 00:09:44,904
After college, I did a teacher training course only to discover that teaching was not for me either.

93
00:09:45,442 --> 00:09:54,932
At a bit of a loose end for a while, I was delighted to discover that there was a career called medical physics and jobs in this area in most big hospitals.

94
00:09:55,673 --> 00:10:02,923
The delight was from the thought that even though I might not understand life deeply, I could contribute meaningfully to it.

95
00:10:04,825 --> 00:10:15,076
My first job was in London in the Royal Free Hospital with a team who were researching lung function and especially the role of aerosols in diagnosis.

96
00:10:15,412 --> 00:10:16,432
and in treatment.

97
00:10:17,254 --> 00:10:27,424
It was a dream start, a small friendly team, enthusiastic about work, curious to try new techniques, a very happy work environment.

98
00:10:28,086 --> 00:10:33,772
Plus a deepening relationship with Adrian, who I had met during the teacher training course.

99
00:10:34,432 --> 00:10:39,437
We were well suited and happy until my mother suddenly took a dislike to him.

100
00:10:40,980 --> 00:10:43,883
Once there was talk of the relationship becoming serious,

101
00:10:44,268 --> 00:10:49,595
and him buying a house, he suddenly became, in her eyes, not good enough for me.

102
00:10:50,235 --> 00:10:56,465
And the sad thing was that I hadn't attached myself enough to withstand her disapproval.

103
00:10:57,505 --> 00:11:01,390
Once she lost confidence in him, I lost confidence in him.

104
00:11:02,172 --> 00:11:05,897
The joy in the relationship went out and eventually we broke up.

105
00:11:06,778 --> 00:11:11,625
In retrospect, I can see that this failure to define myself as separate to my mother

106
00:11:12,009 --> 00:11:15,033
left me with a lot of bitterness and self-doubt.

107
00:11:16,636 --> 00:11:19,200
But, as always, life went on.

108
00:11:19,860 --> 00:11:32,600
And after three years at the Royal Free, I came back to Dublin in my mid-twenties, working in a number of different hospitals, until I took early retirement in 2007, aged 53.

109
00:11:33,821 --> 00:11:36,365
The first decade or so was a happy time.

110
00:11:37,025 --> 00:11:41,292
Friendly colleagues, stimulating work with lots of fascinating research.

111
00:11:41,575 --> 00:11:46,399
enough challenges to make things interesting, enough routine to keep me grounded.

112
00:11:47,081 --> 00:11:48,142
I made good friends.

113
00:11:48,201 --> 00:11:53,807
We played tennis, squash, went hill walking, hired cottages together for holidays.

114
00:11:54,769 --> 00:12:01,735
In retrospect, the most important incident was when colleagues gave me the book, The Tao of Physics.

115
00:12:02,976 --> 00:12:10,705
In retrospect, the most important incident was when colleagues gave me the book, The Tao of Physics,

116
00:12:10,937 --> 00:12:12,279
by Friedrich Capra.

117
00:12:13,380 --> 00:12:19,249
This linked modern physics with Eastern mysticism and opened up a whole new world for me.

118
00:12:19,789 --> 00:12:28,743
I was overjoyed to realise there was another way of understanding life that didn't involve maths and physics, but meditation.

119
00:12:29,923 --> 00:12:31,066
I found D.T.

120
00:12:31,225 --> 00:12:38,416
Suzuki's then mind, Beginner's Mind, and started practising meditation.

121
00:12:38,436 --> 00:12:39,256
A while later,

122
00:12:39,506 --> 00:12:43,633
I found a meditation group and another chapter in life opened up.

123
00:12:43,653 --> 00:12:51,826
Weekly meetings, Dhamma study, retreats, and perhaps most important of all, close friendship with others in the group.

124
00:12:52,307 --> 00:12:54,230
We're still good friends to this day.

125
00:12:55,692 --> 00:13:06,948
One claim to fame for our little group was that we can say we discovered Phante Bodhi Dhamma, invited him to teach his first ever retreat in Dublin back in the mid-1980s.

126
00:13:07,503 --> 00:13:11,586
and he came back for several years afterwards to teach weekend retreats.

127
00:13:12,408 --> 00:13:21,236
Our group was also party to his first 10-day retreat, which was held in Kerry in the late 1990s.

128
00:13:22,759 --> 00:13:28,063
For a decade or more, I couldn't make up my mind between Buddhism and Christianity.

129
00:13:28,625 --> 00:13:36,732
I think some of it stemmed from fear of damnation, because I was now definitely putting a false god before the true god of the catechism.

130
00:13:37,743 --> 00:13:41,288
And some was the sense of identity with the Christian story.

131
00:13:41,749 --> 00:13:50,000
I really wanted to believe it all, whereas the Buddha and the vague notion of enlightenment didn't appeal to me at that personal story level.

132
00:13:50,962 --> 00:14:04,803
I did quite a number of silent meditation retreats with the Carmelite Order, as well as the weekends with Bhante or other Buddhist teachers, and found both forms to be very helpful and inspiring.

133
00:14:04,823 --> 00:14:07,006
The main attraction of Buddhism for me

134
00:14:07,274 --> 00:14:08,995
was the friendship group.

135
00:14:09,015 --> 00:14:12,559
They were my own age, good fun, open to questions.

136
00:14:12,580 --> 00:14:19,148
We used to go out hill walking together, went away on a slighting holiday, celebrated Christmas and birthday party.

137
00:14:20,269 --> 00:14:28,639
On the other hand, the people I met at the Catholic retreats were usually much older than me, more settled in life and more pious than questioning.

138
00:14:29,279 --> 00:14:33,044
So there wasn't much discussion and I never developed any friendships.

139
00:14:34,898 --> 00:14:43,725
I am so grateful that the spiritual aspect of my life opened up because as middle age approached, the lights went out in other areas.

140
00:14:44,606 --> 00:14:57,938
After the disappointment over Adrian, I never again managed to form a committed relationship and the fun went out of medical physics once I became senior, had to take responsibility for services.

141
00:14:57,958 --> 00:15:04,044
It came to a head in my mid-forties while I was also doing a course in the spiritual exercises

142
00:15:04,447 --> 00:15:11,894
of Ignatius Loyola, a form of spiritual training in daily life developed by the Jesuits.

143
00:15:11,913 --> 00:15:15,837
The course is well known for making people more vulnerable than usual.

144
00:15:16,357 --> 00:15:25,807
And in my case, this, along with a combination of work stress and unexpected relationship issues, brought on a mental health crisis.

145
00:15:26,427 --> 00:15:31,111
I couldn't sleep, couldn't stop crying, couldn't find anything to believe in.

146
00:15:32,475 --> 00:15:37,500
I offered to hand in my resignation at work, but the hospital was very decent.

147
00:15:37,942 --> 00:15:45,448
They could see I was unwell and persuaded me to take six months off to think about things and then make a decision.

148
00:15:46,450 --> 00:15:54,038
During those months, as I looked back on life, it seemed to me that the only thing that haven't let me down was meditation practice.

149
00:15:54,698 --> 00:15:58,062
Career and relationships just seemed burdensome now.

150
00:15:58,682 --> 00:16:00,524
Family held no joy at all.

151
00:16:01,096 --> 00:16:14,533
Although I had loved my father very much and we played bridge together for many years, he had died when I was 30 and my relationship with my mother, never strong to start with, went further downhill after that.

152
00:16:15,595 --> 00:16:24,947
I did have good friends from college days and from work and from my meditation group and they were a support but not a reason to live.

153
00:16:25,587 --> 00:16:29,212
The only thing that offered hope was the spiritual realm.

154
00:16:30,408 --> 00:16:34,014
The only thing that offered hope was the spiritual realm.

155
00:16:34,453 --> 00:16:36,376
I'd lost confidence in the world.

156
00:16:37,198 --> 00:16:43,849
And so I made the decision that from now on, spiritual development would be my principal aim in life.

157
00:16:43,869 --> 00:16:45,951
Everything else would come secondary to it.

158
00:16:47,595 --> 00:16:53,443
Being realistic, I knew I didn't have what it would take to head off into the hills as a hermit.

159
00:16:53,965 --> 00:16:58,591
I was too old, 45 at that stage, to be taken in as a novice nun.

160
00:16:59,197 --> 00:17:08,267
Also, the recent breakdown showed me I needed to be gentle with myself, not expect too much, take baby steps rather than giant leaps.

161
00:17:09,048 --> 00:17:24,546
So I changed my work arrangement at the hospital, took a part-time appointment at basic grade level so that I wouldn't have so much responsibility and could organise my work time so as to take months off as needed for retreat and then work full-time between retreats.

162
00:17:25,366 --> 00:17:28,410
This gave me the means to support myself financially

163
00:17:28,744 --> 00:17:31,868
as well as the time needed for spiritual development.

164
00:17:33,090 --> 00:17:46,788
Although I was still undecided between Christianity and Buddhism, this decision was made for me because the teacher who was guiding me through the spiritual exercises cut me off completely once I had to have that breakdown.

165
00:17:47,568 --> 00:17:50,573
It wasn't done unkindly, it was just their policy.

166
00:17:50,913 --> 00:17:56,220
You go to a doctor for mental health issues and come back to spiritual practice when you're balanced again.

167
00:17:57,803 --> 00:18:06,654
Whereas when I told Bhante about the breakdown, he hardly blinked an eye, just told me to get back on the cushion and watch the emotional storm.

168
00:18:07,395 --> 00:18:09,838
From then on, I never wavered.

169
00:18:10,259 --> 00:18:16,406
I realised Buddhism, at least in the form Bhante taught, was what I needed to hold me together in life.

170
00:18:17,528 --> 00:18:21,794
In retrospect, I can see that my life became happier from this point onwards.

171
00:18:22,375 --> 00:18:26,780
I had been happy as a child and a young adult because things were mostly easy.

172
00:18:27,065 --> 00:18:28,066
going my way.

173
00:18:28,526 --> 00:18:39,656
But the happiness that started growing now was coming from a deeper place, from the wisdom of the first noble truth, realizing that nothing in life was going to satisfy.

174
00:18:40,597 --> 00:18:49,385
Along with the inspiration of the third noble truth, trusting in the possibility of being free from suffering, content and happy.

175
00:18:50,727 --> 00:18:56,952
One way I first noticed this growing happiness was the transformation I found in my work colleagues

176
00:18:57,405 --> 00:19:07,117
many whom I had dismissed as foolish or unreliable before I had taken my six months leave, turned out to be wise and trustworthy once I returned.

177
00:19:07,858 --> 00:19:10,201
I could genuinely enjoy their company again.

178
00:19:11,943 --> 00:19:15,828
I also began to see an improvement in my relationship with my mother.

179
00:19:16,450 --> 00:19:23,618
Having taken a decisive step in my own life, a new level of respect started to grow between us.

180
00:19:24,240 --> 00:19:25,961
By the time of her latter years,

181
00:19:26,194 --> 00:19:31,500
Hatred had transformed to love and we were quite at ease with one another.

182
00:19:31,519 --> 00:19:36,324
I moved back to the family home to support her after she turned 90.

183
00:19:38,586 --> 00:19:47,993
Although I'd earlier dreaded the prospect of her becoming dependent on me, caring for her turned out to be as easy as tying my shoelaces.

184
00:19:48,634 --> 00:19:52,377
Not blissful, but just an ordinary...

185
00:19:53,898 --> 00:19:55,240
Although I'd learned earlier

186
00:19:55,792 --> 00:20:07,525
Although I'd earlier dreaded the prospect of her becoming dependent on me, caring for her turned out to be as easy as tying my shoelace.

187
00:20:08,404 --> 00:20:11,808
Not blissful, but just ordinary, not a problem.

188
00:20:12,730 --> 00:20:25,142
Considering my earlier dread of her depending on me and the contrasting simplicity of caring for her in her final years gave me vivid proof of the fruits of spiritual practice.

189
00:20:25,492 --> 00:20:26,894
and brought a lot of happiness.

190
00:20:28,715 --> 00:20:31,278
But I've skipped forward 20 years there.

191
00:20:31,779 --> 00:20:33,942
So back to my midlife crisis now.

192
00:20:34,602 --> 00:20:46,054
It was around this time that Bante started teaching 10 day or longer retreats in various locations in Ireland and the UK before moving to Gaia House as spiritual director.

193
00:20:46,894 --> 00:20:54,403
I became one of the regular attendees and it was towards the end of my first two week retreat that I had an insight

194
00:20:54,771 --> 00:21:02,080
which was possibly a revisiting of my childhood insight of God as a real presence separate to me.

195
00:21:03,241 --> 00:21:14,755
While I was walking along the garden path, I became aware of an expansive presence, a still peaceful knowing which filled the sky and pervaded everything around me.

196
00:21:15,556 --> 00:21:24,626
In that moment, I knew that all my sensory experience was in total harmony with this presence, seeing, hearing, moving,

197
00:21:25,670 --> 00:21:30,595
These were not disturbing or disturbed by the presence.

198
00:21:31,335 --> 00:21:37,560
The only thing that was at odds was my belief in being a separate person, independent.

199
00:21:38,382 --> 00:21:49,992
I saw the experience as a demonstration of the truth of Anatole, and in a flash knew that I would have to lose the identity I called Nori if I was going to attain Nirvana.

200
00:21:51,933 --> 00:21:53,736
Although I'd always wanted insight,

201
00:21:54,339 --> 00:21:57,282
As soon as it came, I wished it hadn't.

202
00:21:57,303 --> 00:22:04,210
It brought up a huge surge of fear, felt like particles of fear were surging up my throat and out of my mouth.

203
00:22:04,930 --> 00:22:18,203
While I haven't felt the presence as threatening in any way, just peaceful, knowing, non-interfering, what frightened me was the knowledge that I'd been making this huge mistake, identifying with the story of my life.

204
00:22:18,943 --> 00:22:21,006
Who could I rely on if not myself?

205
00:22:21,567 --> 00:22:23,689
And I obviously couldn't rely on myself,

206
00:22:23,837 --> 00:22:28,384
because I was the one making the mistake of identifying as me.

207
00:22:28,404 --> 00:22:36,336
This marked another turning point in life, a plunge into fear, but also a waking up.

208
00:22:36,356 --> 00:22:38,059
Bhante's support was wonderful.

209
00:22:38,460 --> 00:22:45,791
He radiated confidence that I could work with the fear, and I had begun to believe him, even before the retreat was over.

210
00:22:46,553 --> 00:22:47,775
It wasn't easy, though.

211
00:22:48,675 --> 00:22:52,561
Since midlife, I'd always had problems sleeping, and now sleeping

212
00:22:55,681 --> 00:22:56,982
It wasn't easy, though.

213
00:22:57,503 --> 00:23:02,951
Since midlife, I'd always had problems sleeping, and now sleep seemed out of the question.

214
00:23:03,894 --> 00:23:09,221
Also, the fearful turbulence led to auditory hallucinations, among other things.

215
00:23:09,803 --> 00:23:24,085
Every now and then, it seemed as though a hurricane was blowing up, the wind was howling, trees smashing, or else someone would be rubbing a packet of crisps right in my ear, or walking with very heavy footsteps round and round my seat.

216
00:23:24,907 --> 00:23:38,607
Fortunately, the visual field wasn't affected, so all I had to do was open my eyes to check that none of this was real, and then go back to working with the anxieties and fear underlying all this strangeness.

217
00:23:40,550 --> 00:23:47,240
What seemed even more fearful was that my face would twitch spontaneously, my tongue waggle around my mouth.

218
00:23:47,882 --> 00:23:53,109
The notion that I was not in control of my own body movements seemed to me horrific.

219
00:23:54,035 --> 00:24:04,289
The twitching and hallucinations eased off after the retreat was over, though fear and anxiety accompanied me for a long time, along with sleeplessness.

220
00:24:05,051 --> 00:24:13,084
The payoff was increased mindfulness because the fearful thoughts were even more upsetting than the present moment feeling of fear.

221
00:24:13,664 --> 00:24:17,851
So for my own peace of mind, I had no choice but to be mindful.

222
00:24:18,632 --> 00:24:22,657
Condemned to the present moment was how I thought of myself.

223
00:24:23,988 --> 00:24:27,230
In time, I started to see how I was benefiting.

224
00:24:27,852 --> 00:24:33,576
Boredom, for example, was a thing of the past, and I had no time for hopelessness or negative thinking.

225
00:24:34,278 --> 00:24:36,359
The call to presence was too strong.

226
00:24:38,221 --> 00:24:42,165
In turn, all my relationships grew more trusting and appreciative.

227
00:24:42,605 --> 00:24:44,909
This was particularly true within the family.

228
00:24:45,368 --> 00:24:53,336
As the bond between myself and my mother strengthened, so also that bond extended to my many cousins, aunts and uncles.

229
00:24:53,991 --> 00:25:00,920
Although circumstances prevent me seeing them often, I sense them as a source of friendship, joy and care.

230
00:25:02,001 --> 00:25:12,734
The deepest gift was the steadily growing faith in the Dhamma, especially the truth of Dukkha and how simply being mindful of Dukkha led to positive change.

231
00:25:13,615 --> 00:25:23,086
I was very chuffed when in 2003 Bhante asked me to assist him in teaching.

232
00:25:23,826 --> 00:25:31,217
I felt this as a great honour and a confirmation that I had turned a corner in life.

233
00:25:32,999 --> 00:25:53,547
Trust in the Dhamma was my saviour, when in 2005 I was diagnosed with throat cancer, which was treated with radiotherapy, giving me a good seven years until it returned with a vengeance.

234
00:25:53,694 --> 00:26:01,041
needing to not just major but heroic surgery in 2013, with only a 50-50 chance of survival.

235
00:26:01,882 --> 00:26:04,684
It also meant losing my voice box.

236
00:26:04,704 --> 00:26:21,119
I've written about that in some essays on the website, so I won't say much more here, except that this unwanted turn of events brought deeper faith and insight, along with its natural share of sorrow.

237
00:26:22,348 --> 00:26:28,875
And so let's skip forward to 2020, when after a fall in which she broke her hip, my mother died.

238
00:26:28,894 --> 00:26:31,538
A peaceful death, I'm happy to say.

239
00:26:31,998 --> 00:26:35,721
And I was with her at the time, which was a gift I will always treasure.

240
00:26:36,542 --> 00:26:44,130
By this stage, I was long retired and had always thought of coming to live near Satipanya after my mother's death.

241
00:26:44,150 --> 00:26:46,152
She died in January 2020.

242
00:26:46,551 --> 00:26:51,376
And in March, I came to Satipanya to join the final month of the winter retreat.

243
00:26:52,453 --> 00:26:55,896
But then the COVID lockdown happened and I never went home.

244
00:26:55,936 --> 00:26:59,740
Initially, it was because it was considered unsafe to travel.

245
00:27:00,122 --> 00:27:11,532
But as the weeks and months went by, it became clear that there really was no good reason to go back to Dublin and that I would be far happier staying at Santa Pania.

246
00:27:11,553 --> 00:27:21,583
Luckily, Bante was also pleased to be able to offload some of the management responsibilities and I was happy to take on more of the teaching.

247
00:27:22,153 --> 00:27:30,462
So the COVID lockdown was for me a great blessing, opening up a new phase in life for me, which I trust is very beneficial.

248
00:27:31,683 --> 00:27:46,660
To mark this new phase, I took lay ordination in 2021 to help me take heart in the Dhamma as the inspiration for my life and dedicate the remainder of my time on earth to practice in accordance with the Dhamma Buddha Sangha.

249
00:27:50,571 --> 00:28:07,215
To mark this new phase, I took lay ordination in 2021 to help me take heart in the Dhamma as the inspiration for my life and dedicate the remainder of my time on earth to practice in accordance with the Buddha Dhamma Sangha.

250
00:28:08,258 --> 00:28:12,403
Part of this is an annual retreat, which I take during the winter months.

251
00:28:13,105 --> 00:28:20,275
As a treat for my 70th birthday, I booked a house in Portugal from January last year to the middle of February

252
00:28:20,676 --> 00:28:32,233
and spent my 70th birthday exploring the joys and woes of the inner life, opening some doors in my mind, making peace with those that remain stubbornly closed.

253
00:28:34,037 --> 00:28:40,165
I honestly cannot think of a more satisfying way to mark my 70th birthday.

254
00:28:41,186 --> 00:28:43,250
A final word about friendship.

255
00:28:43,971 --> 00:28:49,619
One wonderful aspect of Dharma practice is that you meet the best of people, considerate,

256
00:28:49,853 --> 00:28:57,483
honest, good-natured, kind, making the best of life's vicissitudes, interested in spiritual matters.

257
00:28:58,144 --> 00:29:00,307
It's a heaven realm from that point of view.

258
00:29:00,807 --> 00:29:04,292
And I want to thank all of you reading this for the long...

259
00:29:06,215 --> 00:29:08,719
It's a heaven realm from that point of view.

260
00:29:09,140 --> 00:29:15,509
And I want to thank all of you reading or listening to this for the deep contribution you have made to my life.

261
00:29:16,549 --> 00:29:19,354
I want to finish by thanking Bhante Bodhidharma

262
00:29:19,789 --> 00:29:25,276
for forgiving my many mistakes and encouraging me at every opportunity.

263
00:29:26,057 --> 00:29:34,967
Although his Joada Beaver can sometimes be infuriating, why can't he just get upset like any normal human being, I'd be thinking to myself.

264
00:29:34,987 --> 00:29:44,217
There is always some small corner of my mind that's willing to trust his good humour as a guide through whatever difficulty is presented.

265
00:29:44,936 --> 00:29:47,400
Just as the Rosary guided me in childhood,

266
00:29:47,768 --> 00:30:00,022
Vante's teaching, friendship and unstinting support have guided my latter years, gentling the decline into old age, inspiring faith in what lies beyond.

